            <p>N. Y.<lb/>
                Sharon Springs<lb/>
                July 21<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 5650<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I write to inform<lb/> you that I am staying at this<lb/> place and my address is<lb/> &#34;Landon Cottage&#44; Sharon<lb/> Springs N. Y.&#34;  Before leaving<lb/> the city&#44; I called on Dr. H. P.<lb/> Mendes to make arrangements<lb/> with him for the continuation<lb/> of the instruction during my<lb/> absence but failing to meet<lb/> him&#44; I arranged with Speaker<lb/> that he should take temporary<lb/> charge of my classes.  I was<lb/> very sorry to be obliged to<lb/> suspend my work so suddenly<lb/> especially as my lecture on<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>&#34;Judaism and Ethics&#34; is all pre&#45;<lb/>&#45;pared and in manuscript<lb/> but I suddenly became alarmingly<lb/> weak and my physician&#44; Dr Meyer&#44;<lb/> told me that the only way to<lb/> avoid a serious illness was to<lb/> leave the city at once for rest and<lb/> change of air.  I am feeling<lb/> much better but have not yet<lb/> recovered my normal strength.<lb/>  I shall&#44; however&#44; be ready&#44; the<lb/> Lord willing&#44; to take either the<lb/> lecture after Tishea Be&#39;ab or the<lb/> closing lecture of the season.<lb/>  After the lecture&#44; I shall&#44; if the<lb/> summer term be not concluded&#44;<lb/> continue the instruction in the<lb/> classes.  Awaiting your further<lb/> disposition in the matter&#44; I am&#44; Sir<lb/> very sincerely yours<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
